license: "CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0"
abstract: >-
  Academic monograph examining the convergence of CRISPR-based genome editing
  systems and artificial intelligence, from molecular mechanism to clinical
  application to sociotechnical governance. Structured in three parts across
  nine chapters: Part I reviews CRISPR architectures and AI-driven design and
  optimisation; Part II maps the therapeutic landscape for rare diseases and
  hereditary cancer syndromes; Part III analyses regulatory frameworks,
  bioethics, STS perspectives, and prospective scenarios for 2026–2030.
  Approximately 58,000 words and 384+ bibliographic entries. Produced through
  transparent hybrid human–AI collaboration at the Universidad de Granada
  within the framework of Horizon Europe projects PREDI-LYNCH (Grant 101213916)
  and LATE-AYA (Grant 101214879).
keywords:
  - CRISPR genome editing
  - artificial intelligence in biomedicine
  - Science and Technology Studies
  - regulatory governance
  - rare diseases
  - Horizon Europe
